<statement><div><p>Consider the three numbers <m>{45}</m>, <m>{180}</m> and <m>{162}</m>.</p>
<p>Find both the greatest common factor (<m>\text{GCF}</m>) and least common multiple (<m>\text{LCM}</m>) of the numbers.</p>

<br/>

<p>(a) <m>\text{GCF}({45}, {180}, {162}) =</m> <fillin characters="5" name="ans1"/> </p>
<p/>

<br/>

<p>(b) <m>\text{LCM}({45}, {180}, {162}) =</m> <fillin characters="5" name="ans2"/> </p>
<p/></div></statement>
<solution><div><h3>Worked Solution</h3>
<p>We first express each of the numbers in its prime factorization:</p>

<p style="margin-left:30px"><m>{45} = {3}^{2}

    {\hspace{2px}\times \hspace{2px}}
    {5}
    ^{1}

    {}
    {}
    ^{}

    {}
    {}
    ^{}

</m></p>

<p style="margin-left:30px"><m>{180} = {2}^{2}

    {\hspace{2px}\times \hspace{2px}}
    {3}
    ^{2}

    {\hspace{2px}\times \hspace{2px}}
    {5}
    ^{1}

    {}
    {}
    ^{}

</m></p>

<p style="margin-left:30px"><m>{162} = {2}^{1}

    {\hspace{2px}\times \hspace{2px}}
    {3}
    ^{4}

    {}
    {}
    ^{}

    {}
    {}
    ^{}

</m></p>

<br/>

<p>(a) To find the <m>\text{GCF}</m>, we take the <alert>smallest power</alert> of each prime appearing in all three prime factorizations. Therefore,</p>

<p style="margin-left:30px"><md number="yes">
<mrow>\text{GCF}({45},{180},{162}) \amp = {3}^{2}

    {}
    {}
    ^{}

    {}
    {}
    ^{}</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = \mathbf{{9}}</mrow>
</md></p>

<br/>

<p>(b) To find the <m>\text{LCM}</m>, we take the <alert>largest power</alert> of each prime appearing in the factorizations. Therefore,</p>

<p style="margin-left:30px"><md number="yes">
<mrow>\text{LCM}({45},{180},{162}) \amp = {2}^{2}

    {\hspace{2px}\times \hspace{2px}}
    {3}
    ^{4}

    {\hspace{2px}\times \hspace{2px}}
    {5}
    ^{1}

    {}
    {}
    ^{}</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = \mathbf{{1620}}</mrow>
</md></p></div></solution>
<answer><p><m>9</m></p></answer>
<answer><p><m>1620</m></p></answer>
